This includes help with checking and understanding privacy and safety settings. They also told us parents shouldn’t be afraid to set boundaries; teens expect and even welcome them. Safety features like Family Pairing are tools to allow families to set parameters, which are especially important while teens are starting out online.","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips1_title":"“Help me understand the rules”","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips2_body":"Teens want trusted adults to be interested in their digital lives and to recognize how important they are to them. Teens feel supported when they know they have an ally who is available to talk to them. Don’t be afraid to start a conversation. They appreciate hearing you understand things can go wrong online, and you’ll be there to help if they do, no matter the scale of the problem.","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips2_title":"“Be available to chat”","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips3_body":"When your teen seeks your help, it’s a positive step. They may be feeling vulnerable, scared, embarrassed, or upset, so let them know how happy you are that they’ve reached out. When they share their problem, be mindful of your reaction; teens told us that responding with anger discourages them from seeking help again. Also, avoid downplaying their concerns, even if you don’t fully understand why they’re upset. Listen without blame, ask questions, and focus on finding solutions together. If they’ve broken rules, teens expect consequences, but they also desire guidance on how to avoid similar mistakes in the future.","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips3_title":"“Don't panic when things go wrong”","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips4_body":"Teens understand that trust is earned, and expect adult supervision, especially younger teens. Like in the physical world, teens feel they should gain more autonomy as they mature. Every family is different and the pace at which a teen moves toward independent use of technology will vary, but if your teen knows how to use platforms safely and turns to you for help when needed, it builds a strong foundation for trust.","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips4_title":"“Trust me”","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips5_body":"Striking a balance between a teenager’s expectation of privacy and ensuring their safety, both online and offline, is a challenging aspect of parenting. When your teen asks you not to follow them on a platform, it’s natural to worry, but they might just want space to connect with friends privately. There may be good reasons why you feel following your teen’s account is necessary. If so, teens say they want to understand your reasons and to explore ways to build trust. Older teens told us they feel protective of younger relatives and naturally look out for them online, so consider if someone else could monitor their activity in your place.","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips5_title":"“Respect my privacy”","phototextApp_digitalParentingTips_safetyTips_body":"At TikTok Notes, we’re committed to working in partnership with parents and caregivers as you support your teen’s digital experience. We understand that staying updated of changing trends and emerging platforms can be overwhelming. We want to help simplify this by sharing insights into the kind of support teens genuinely appreciate from trusted adults. And who better to provide guidance on their needs than teens themselves?
